IMF needs more Lagarde
Davos - Lagarde once said she was open to serving another five years as the president of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
She should be reappointed.
The IMF has never had a better leadership than her, and the IMF Board should give her the opportunity to complete the work she has started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, taking over an institution that was plagued by crisis.
2008's global financial meltdown and its subsequent economic ripple effect ruined the credibility of western-led multilateral lending institutions and the free market "Washington Consensus".
Lagarde's leadership helped IMF regain its reputation.
Many eyes turned to her personal quality — — it's only natural.
She is candid, powerful, warm and moving.
Countries' officials who met her (often in subtle environments) all expressed that she dares to say the difficult reality, while also being a sensitive listener.
For a leader of an institution that must negotiate terms rather than dictate everything, these are important qualities.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed to be restructured, otherwise they would have to build a firewall to prevent financial contagion. The hard truth was unwelcome, but the Europeans still went ahead and did it.
Similarly, she loudly called for IMF support to be provided to some countries — Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine — which are crucial for global stability.
And there are countless more examples.
The IMF is not good at innovation, nor is it usually passionate.
Lagarde began to change that.
In the process, she gave this organization, which often dispenses bitter medicine, a human face.
For example, managing the Middle East refugee crisis was not within the IMF's scope of responsibilities.
But under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its plans, allowing the Jordanian government to allocate more funds to help the refugees in the camps (more than one million people living in refugee camps within Jordan's borders) who were displaced by the conflicts in Syria and Iraq.
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola outbreak occurred in West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF in using its callable capital to provide debt relief to the countries affected by the crisis, allowing them to improve the salaries of doctors and nurses — a first for the IMF to use its own capital in this way.
In addition, Lagarde recognized that the world today is facing three major challenges, and she took action against them.
First, she strongly advocated for more women to join the workforce, and she herself is a shining example of a woman in a leadership position.
From Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urged leaders to stop wasting such a vast talent pool - and to tap into their economic potential.
Secondly, under her leadership, the IMF has also addressed the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not just a basic issue of fairness.
IMF's research emphasizes the direct connection between reducing income inequality and improving economic growth.
IMF is not the first institution to prove this, but its position makes this issue more prominent and pressing.
Lagarde has always been committed to promoting this point, which is a key factor in increasing its urgency.
Thirdly, Lagarde has played an important role in helping the world recognize the full impact of technological transitions — some of which will have devastating effects.
For example, automation will continue to improve the efficiency and lower the costs of manufacturing, but it also means that the number of jobs created by economic growth is not as much as before.
This new emerging reality's political, economic and social consequences deserve to be recognized and seriously studied.
Lagarde made IMF the core of this work.
Critics will say it's time for developing countries to lead IMF.
After all, Lagarde is the 11th consecutive European to hold this position, and Europe has such a privilege, which is hard to be accepted by the world today.
Some also say that Greece's austerity measures supported by IMF have not been fully effective, which proves she has become disconnected from the ordinary people.
Some people will point out that she faces allegations related to the financial scandal in France, which will distract her from her work at IMF.
Critics argue that IMF cannot afford to be distracted again by such a scandal, especially after her predecessor Dominique Strauss-Kahn was embroiled in one.
Let's analyze these opposing views one by one.
IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from outside of Europe and America.
The goal of ending this Western privilege is to make the selection process of leaders based on merit, not politics.
Lagarde is the best choice for IMF president, and emerging powers such as the BRIC countries (Brazil, Russia, India and China) have not jointly proposed a candidate to replace her.
Perhaps the fact that a European is in charge of IMF is also one of the factors that helped IMF decide to include the yuan in the currency basket that determines the special drawing rights' value last December.
Moreover, Lagarde showed impressive political flexibility to finally convince both the Republican and Democratic parties in the US Congress to approve the IMF governance reform, which not only strengthened IMF's ammunition to curb financial crises, but also better reflects the dynamic changes in the global economy.
For example, the BRIC countries have now entered the top ten shareholder list of IMF.
In the Greece issue, Lagarde made some straightforward comments last year, which people thought were rather personal and not suitable for a head of IMF.
But she is not the culprit who brings economic pain to the Greeks, she fully demonstrated during her tenure at IMF that no president in the history of IMF has done as much as she has in leading IMF to alleviate people's suffering in crisis.
Finally, the charges against Lagarde were opposed by the French prosecutor general, and Lagarde was only slightly involved at most.
The world needs a leader who is committed to making the world safer and more prosperous.
Lagarde has proven to be such a leader, and she is committed to making IMF adapt to the 21st century.
She deserves the opportunity to complete her work.
